The inverse Faraday effect is the reverse of the Faraday effect. Recall that the Faraday effect refers to the polarization rotation of light induced by a static magnetization along the light propagation direction [119]. Correspondingly, the inverse Faraday effect refers to the generation of static magnetization induced by circularly polarized light propagating inside the material (Fig.Â 12d) [229, 230]. In this case, the angular momentum from an oscillating electric field E(t)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
