				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varvec{M} \propto \varvec{E}(\omega )\times \varvec{E}^*(\omega )$$\end{document}. The inverse Faraday effect is a nonlinear phenomenon [231]. It does not require absorption but is rather based on a Raman-like coherent optical scattering process. Consequently, this effect is non-thermal and takes place on a femtosecond timescale. The laser-induced magnetization can be used for ultrafast control of magnetic devices [232, 233]. It can also cause the Faraday rotation for a subsequent probe light, which induces a matter-mediated light-light interaction.

